<h3>An Invitation to Test</h3>
<p>If faith is the engine that drives every meaningful action in life, then the question is not whether you are capable of faith&mdash;you exercise it every day. The question is whether you are willing to direct that capacity toward the deepest questions of your existence.</p>
<p>An ancient teacher named Alma proposed an experiment. He was not speaking to believers. He was speaking to people who had been cast out, who had nothing, who doubted. And he did not ask them to believe. He asked them to try:</p>
<p>&ldquo;If ye will awake and arouse your faculties, even to an experiment upon my words, and exercise a particle of faith, yea, even if ye can no more than desire to believe, let this desire work in you, even until ye believe in a manner that ye can give place for a portion of my words&rdquo; (Alma 32:27).</p>
<p>Note the honesty of that invitation. He did not demand certainty. He asked only for desire&mdash;a willingness to begin. He then compared the word of God to a seed. Plant it. Give it space. Observe what happens. &ldquo;If it be a true seed, or a good seed, if ye do not cast it out by your unbelief&hellip; behold, it will begin to swell within your breasts; and when you feel these swelling motions, ye will begin to say within yourselves&mdash;It must needs be that this is a good seed, for it beginneth to enlarge my soul; yea, it beginneth to enlighten my understanding; yea, it beginneth to be delicious to me&rdquo; (Alma 32:28).</p>
<p>This is a constructivist and pragmatic approach to spiritual truth&mdash;terms your own philosophical training may recognize. It does not ask you to accept a conclusion before testing it. It asks you to plant a seed and observe the fruit. Judge the tree by what it produces. If the seed swells, if light increases, if something delicious enters your experience that was not there before&mdash;you will have your evidence. Not proof that would satisfy a laboratory, but evidence that satisfies the whole person.</p>

<h3>What the Experiment May Produce</h3>
<p>Those who have tried this experiment across centuries and cultures report remarkably consistent results: a sense of clarity where confusion lived before, a deep peace that transcends circumstance, a warmth in the heart that is unlike anything else, a feeling of conviction and closeness to something real and good. Two of Christ&rsquo;s disciples, walking the road to Emmaus after His death, encountered a stranger who explained the scriptures to them. They did not recognize Him until He broke bread with them&mdash;and then they said to one another, &ldquo;Did not our heart burn within us, while he talked with us by the way?&rdquo; (Luke 24:32).</p>
<p>That burning is what the experiment may produce. It is not hysteria. It is not emotion whipped up by a crowd. It is the quiet recognition of truth arriving in a heart that was ready for it.</p>

<h3>How to Begin</h3>
<p>If you are willing, here is how to begin. Find a place that is private and free from distraction. Calm your body and your mind. You cannot do this wrong&mdash;there is no single formula or technique. Prayer is an honest personal effort. Find the innermost part of who you are, and direct your thoughts and your desire toward the source of truth&mdash;whatever or whoever that may be.</p>
<p>Ask, honestly, whether God is real. Ask whether Jesus Christ was truly His Son. Ask whether you should believe in Him and follow Him. And then listen. Not for a thunderclap. Listen for something quieter: a peace in your mind, a warmth in your heart, a sense that what you are doing is right. &ldquo;If any of you lack wisdom, let him ask of God, that giveth to all men liberally, and upbraideth not; and it shall be given him&rdquo; (James 1:5).</p>
<p>If nothing comes immediately, do not despair. The Lord counseled patience: &ldquo;Wait on the Lord. Be of good courage and he shall strengthen thine heart&rdquo; (Psalm 27:14). And know this: not everyone receives a dramatic answer. To some it is given to know by the power of the Holy Ghost. To others it is given to believe on their words (D&amp;C 46:13&ndash;14). Both are gifts. Both are real.</p>
<p>We promise you that if you undertake this experiment honestly&mdash;with real intent and an open heart&mdash;you will discover that the seed is good. The fruit of the tree of faith is real, and it is worth every risk required to plant it.</p>

