<h3>The Daily Cross</h3>
<p>Jesus said, &ldquo;If any man will come after me, let him deny himself, and take up his cross daily, and follow me&rdquo; (Luke 9:23). The key word is <em>daily</em>. The cross is not something you picked up once at baptism and set down. It is something you carry every morning when you wake and every evening when you kneel. It is the ongoing surrender of your will to His&mdash;not as a grim duty, but as the path to the only freedom that lasts.</p>
<p>The covenant disciple&rsquo;s cross is the law of consecration lived in the heart before it is lived in the community. It is giving everything&mdash;time, talent, resources, pride, ambition, comfort&mdash;to the Lord&rsquo;s purposes. And it is receiving back from Him something infinitely greater: the promise that &ldquo;all that my Father hath shall be given&rdquo; to those who are faithful (D&amp;C 84:38).</p>

<h3>The Commandments in the Mirror</h3>
<p>Christ gave His commandments in His own words, without interpretation by theologians: Abide in Me. Repent. Follow Me. Let your light shine. Love your enemies. Deny yourself. Forgive offenders&mdash;not seven times, but seventy times seven. Be a servant. Feed My sheep. Be born again. Watch and pray. Spread the gospel. These are not suggestions. They are commandments. The covenant disciple must ask: Am I keeping these? Not perfectly&mdash;perfection is the direction, not the entrance requirement. But am I keeping them? Am I trying? Am I growing?</p>
<p>Hypocrisy is to profess standards and beliefs contrary to one&rsquo;s real character or behavior. It is the great danger of the established faithful&mdash;those who have learned the vocabulary of Zion without living its meaning. Few were condemned more harshly by Christ than the self-righteous Pharisees (Matthew 23). The covenant disciple must hold the mirror of the commandments close and look without flinching.</p>

<h3>Grace for the Covenant Keeper</h3>
<p>Grace is not only for converts. It is especially for the faithful who have grown weary, who have stumbled on the path they know to be right, who carry the weight of covenants they have not always kept perfectly. Paul wrote, &ldquo;By grace are ye saved through faith&rdquo; (Ephesians 2:8). The Book of Mormon adds, &ldquo;It is by grace that we are saved, after all we can do&rdquo; (2 Nephi 25:23). And what is our &ldquo;all&rdquo;? It is our honest effort, our sincere repentance, our willingness to get up every time we fall and face the Lord again.</p>
<p>The people of King Benjamin experienced this transformation and testified: &ldquo;The Spirit of the Lord Omnipotent has wrought a mighty change in us, or in our hearts, that we have no more disposition to do evil, but to do good continually&rdquo; (Mosiah 5:2). But even that mighty change requires maintenance. Alma asked the searching questions that every covenant disciple must answer: &ldquo;Have ye spiritually been born of God? Have ye received his image in your countenances? Have ye experienced this mighty change in your hearts?&rdquo; (Alma 5:14). And then the harder question: &ldquo;If ye have experienced a change of heart, and if ye have felt to sing the song of redeeming love, I would ask, can ye feel so now?&rdquo; (Alma 5:26).</p>
<p>Can you feel so now? If the answer is yes, press forward with gratitude. If the answer is no, or <em>not as I once did</em>, then repent&mdash;not with shame but with hope. The Atonement of Christ is not a one-time transaction. It is an ongoing covenant relationship. &ldquo;The Lord your Redeemer suffered death in the flesh; wherefore he suffered the pain of all men, that all men might repent and come unto him&rdquo; (D&amp;C 18:11). His arms are still outstretched. Return to Him.</p>
<p>Even an elect disciple of Christ can fall from grace (D&amp;C 20:32&ndash;34, Hebrews 6:4&ndash;6). This is not said to terrify but to awaken. The path requires vigilance. The daily cross requires daily carrying.</p>

